</td><td>&#x02212;5.58<break/>(&#x000b1;1.58)**</td><td>&#x02212;8.25<break/>(&#x000b1;1.26)**</td><td>&#x02212;1.96<break/>(&#x000b1;1.82)</td><td>&#x02212;1.16<break/>(&#x000b1;1.40)</td></tr></tbody></table><table-wrap-foot><p>CAPS: Clinician Administered PTSD Scale; CGI-I: Clinical Global Impressions Scale- improvement; MADRS: Montgomery Asberg Depression Rating Scale; SDS: Sheehan Disability Scale; SE: Standar Error; VAS-D: Visual Analogue Scale- Depression; VAS-A: Visual Analogue Scale- Anxiety; *: p &#x0003c; 0.05; **: p &#x0003c; 0.01.</p></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap></p><p>Adverse events are listed in Table&#x000a0;<xref rid="Tab4" ref-type="table">4</xref>. There were no significant group differences in the incidence of adverse events. The most commonly reported were stomach cramps/upset (n = 5), drowsiness (N = 4), sweating (N = 3) and increased appetite (N = 3). Due to side effects, dosage was reduced to 10 mg in 1 participant in the escitalopram group. Adherence to treatment was acceptable in both groups, with only 2 participants in each group withdrawn.<table-wrap id="Tab4"><label>Table 4</label><caption><p>
